segments.text: Burns, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, and the places where they were born and died, the date and place of your birth, the schools you attended before you went to Texas A&M, and any other recollections of your childhood that you have that you might want to record for us?
Well, my father was Arthur Burns, and he was born January the 2nd, 1850.
I don't know whether it was 52 or 53.
He was an active cattleman all of his life.
Went up the trail a number of years.
Seven years, I think, drove the trail.
He died in 1914.
He was, where was he born?
Born in DeWitt County of one of a family of 10 children who the father was Columbus Burns, the first white child born in what now DeWitt County.
He was a son of Arthur Burns, my great grandfather.
who came to Texas from Pike County, Missouri in 1826 and built a log cabin on the east side of Guadalupe River and obtained from the Mexican government a league of land.
His son, Squire Burns, a laborer,
He had previously been married, and several children came with him and his wife, I think his third wife, when they came to Texas.
But Columbus Burns, my own grandfather, who was born in 1829 and died in 1899 in my home where I was read, was the first white child born in that area.
He married a DeMoss, and of that union there were 10 children.
five boys and five girls.
My father was the second of the family.
My mother was born Mary Evie Cardwell, was born in 1855 at the old Cardwell homestead four miles north of Cuero.
Her father was Crockett Cardwell,
who was born in 1812 during the Battle of New Orleans and came to Texas in the early 1830s, 1833 I believe, and came to Gonzales.
My mother's mother, my own grandmother, Ann Eliza White, married Crockett Cardwell in 1846.
No.
They married 1840.
They bought the old Friar original homestead property north of Cuero in 1846.
That's where my mother was born.
She had a brother that lived
died in early childhood as a boy eight years old.
Anna Eliza White was a mother and father left Elizabeth down in North Carolina in 1829 to come to Texas, and he died en route in Alabama.
And my grandmother, Anna Eliza White, was born in 1824.
She had four brothers.
Let's see, yeah, I believe four, maybe five.
They all came to Texas, and her mother remarried a fellow named Tomlinson and came on to old Washington on the Brazos with Austin's colonists and Berta Gonzalez.
And she was in Gonzales when Sandy Anna ran them out.
And one of her stepbrothers, a Tumbleson, was in the Battle of the Alamo.
That bunch that went from Gonzales to San Antonio was killed in the Battle of the Alamo.
I've heard her say many times that when Sandy Anna ran them out of Gonzales, she rode a big old gray car-chair horse from
Gonzales to the Battle of San Jacinto.
It was within 12 miles of the Battle of San Jacinto when it was fought.
They didn't route there.
They could see Houston's army in front of them, the dust from across that Eagle Lake prairie, and Santa Ana's army behind them.
So it was pretty squally.
She was a great historian, an Irish gal, and had a lot of energy and a lot of gold.
She lived
to be 90 years old and died my mother's own at Cuero.
They were all of the early, real early settlers in South Texas.
It was a big family connection over the Burns.
Dr. John W. Burns made quite a reputation.
He and his two sons, his doctors there.
Louis Burns was a farmer, stock farmer north of Quero there for many, many years.
And old Judge Jim Burns was judge, county attorney over at, lawyer over at Goliad and operated a private bank there for many, many years.
It was a big family connection, but most of them are gone.
Very few of them survived.
I was born in July 1895, after the family had moved from the old Cardwell homestead four miles north of Quirrell.
My father had built my mother a new home there in late 1894, early 95, and that's where I was born.
I was the only child of a family of five that was born in Cuero.
The rest of them were born at the old Cardwell homestead north of Cuero, two brothers and two sisters.
John C. Burns, who was later head of animal husbandry department at A&M College,
an 0-4 man, and A.C. Burns, born in 1886, an 0-7 man, and two sisters, Mrs. J.W.
Hawke of Cuero, and Mrs. Evie Locker.
Mrs. Locker's deceased, and John C. Burns' deceased.
The other sister, Mrs. Hawke, still lives in Cuero, in the rest home there.
A.C. Burns, a veterinarian, a graduate of A&M in 07, graduate in veterinary medicine at Ohio State in 1910, and has practiced in the Cleveland area until retirement a few years ago.
I went to public school at Cuero and probably reached the seventh, eighth grade, not over the eighth grade, I don't believe.
They picked me up, sent me to Allen Academy about 1910, 11.
Old man John Rivers Allen was operating at an academy that had a real good school.
I can't remember whether I went there in ten or eleven.
A number of the boys that I went to school there, some few went to A&M later.
A bunch of those boys went to Swanee later.
A whole bunch of Waco boys I know went to Suwannee.
I entered A&M College in the fall of 1912 and finished the spring of 1916 in animal husbandry.
What factors were involved in your choice of A&M?
You had a brother who had been there.
Two of them had been there before.
I don't know if there was any choice about it.
It just went.
Just automatic.
Just automatic.
That's right.
No other school was considered.
If I ever had any other thought, I don't remember it.
Did you go through any particular procedures to enter school there?
I mean, did you apply for admission?
Did you have to take a test or anything like that?

Yeah, I think I went out there and put in an application to accept him, but I think when I got out there, they gave me some examinations, one of which I didn't pass, and they made me take some work over, which I flunked then promptly.
You had completed all of the instruction at Allen Academy, though, by the time you applied.
No, just enough to get into A&M.
I didn't graduate at Allen.
Was there a minimum age entrance to A&M at that point?
Did you have to be a certain number of years old before you could enter A&M?
I don't know.
I finished before I was 21 years old.
I finished June and I was 21 July following graduation.
So you must have been, what, about 16 when you entered.
Probably you couldn't have gotten in any younger than that.
No, I was about right.
Well, since you...
Allen was then, of course, a military school as it is now.
No, it wasn't.
It was not a military school then?
No, no, no.
I see.
So then you had not had any...
I had had no military training at all when I went to A&M.
You were probably aware of some of the military aspects.
Oh, I'd been out there.
I had a brother.
This older brother was head of animal husbandry department living on the campus.
So I knew everybody out there.
You knew all the faculty members.
Oh, I was hazed two years instead of one.
You bet.
I knew all of them.
You bet.
So you say you were hazed two years instead of one.
Oh, yes.
The year before you got there and the first year you were there.
The year before, because I had this brother there and everybody knew him.
John Burns' brother.
Boy, we were making hard on him.
Well, I had the best time of anybody.
So when I went out there, I didn't know any strangers, so I knew everybody.
A number of people have commented to me that the only people who hazed you were the ones who really liked you.
That's exactly right.
That boy that didn't want to be hazed was not hazed.
That's all baloney about him being cruel and everything.
I've seen some boys ostracized down there because he just couldn't take it.
But I've never had more fun than I had during my fishing sophomore year because I took it and then I dished it out when I was a sophomore.
Well, I imagine the boy who didn't want to be hazed wasn't hazed, and he wasn't liked very well.
He wasn't very popular, that's right.
You were, of course, completely familiar with it, and I guess there were really no surprises to you when you got there.
Oh, yeah, no, there wasn't any surprises.
You knew what to expect and everything like that.
You, I believe, entered L Company as a fish.
Did you have some choice in that matter?
Well, they just put you in a company where they wanted you.
And as a member of L Company, where did you live?
Austin Hall, the oldest on the campus, that's right.
We carried wood and water, a wood stove and a bucket and a wash basin there.
a table and two beds and about two chairs, and that was it.
You had, what, two people in the room?
Yeah, me and another boy, and I don't even remember who the other boy was right at the moment.
I believe a boy named Hans Rice, R-E-U-S-S, from Cuero.
And they moved us.
If he and I started rooming there, they moved us later to the top story of Milner Hall after the strike.
So you had a strike down there, too.
This was in?
Thirteen.
Thirteen, yeah.
That's when a bunch of boys left school.
That's right.
That's exactly right.
Well, after that, they closed up.
They moved a whole bunch of us from Austin Hall.
The L Company was in Austin Hall and the fourth floor of Milner.
So Austin was not big enough for the whole company?
I reckon.
But anyhow, they moved us.
and put us upstairs on the fourth floor, I reckon, of Milner Hall.
Well, Milner probably had central heat, I believe, at that point, so you didn't have to carry wood anymore.
That's right.
We carried many a trunk up those steps.
I imagine so.
In Milner, then, I gather they had a bathroom on every floor.
Oh, yeah.
They had showers on every floor, yeah.
Whereas when living in Austin Hall, we had to go to that old bath, the old, what do we call it, down there, where they had showers.
You'd take your clothes and soap and towels and go down there and take a bath.
And then go back to the Austin Hall.
That's right.
So when you were moved out, then what'd they do?
Just kind of close Austin Hall?
I think they closed Austin Hall and later made a storage place over there.
Probably some other personnel lived there for a while.
It was an old one, sure enough.
I imagine during the war or after when they had an increase in enrollment, they probably opened it up again.
Probably did.
I wasn't there at that time, of course.
You indicated that there was a strike in 1913.
What do you recall that was the cause of that?
Oh, I don't know.
One of the factors was hazing.
They had let some boys go, and they wanted to reinstate them, and they weren't pleased with Milner, who was president.
There was some other factors that I don't remember now.
We entered into it and of course there's always a bunch that wanted to blow up.
And they lost a lot of good students.
They lost a lot of good men that left during that strike and never did come back.
And of course some of them did come back.
Now this was, the school had dismissed some people who were guilty of hazing.
Oh yeah, that's right.
And the other boys in...
They took exception to it.
They wanted to reinstate it.
That's right.
And I think it was over in D Company.
I'm not sure where it was.
Seemed to me like it was in Foster Hall.
D Company was in Foster Hall.
And I don't remember the particulars of it.
And they had several mass meetings and...
haranguing about quitting and this, that, and the other.
Well, how did the strike come in?
Did the students refuse to go to school anymore?
Well, they just decided not to go to school.
Went home.
The others stayed there and they opened classes and went back to school.
About how long did this whole business go on, do you remember?
Probably a week.
I don't remember.
That's been a long time ago.
Yeah, I'm sure.
I know it has.
It's been a lot of things since that time.
I imagine there was probably a good bit of difference in life in the dormitory from when you moved from Austin to Milner, wasn't it?
Not a great deal.
You still had a guard every night.
You had a guard over at Austin Hall.
You had a guard at the middle of the same.
It wasn't much different.
A little more convenient.
We didn't have to carry wood and water.
You didn't have to carry wood and water, so that was a little bit easier.
You still had a few things to do for the upperclassmen.
Oh, the upperclassmen, it was just like being in the Army.
There was no monkey business about that.
Now, they ran the school.
They ran the...
company and they were respected and what they said went.
There wasn't any monkey business about it.
Junior and senior classes, of course, upperclassmen, they were absolutely in charge.
Their word was the law.
That was it, that's right.
In addition to having this
this control over the freshmen, did the upperclassmen have any other privileges that they could exercise?
Oh, yeah, they could go to town, they could stay out, they'd get off, get furloughed.
The freshmen couldn't get furloughed.
And I think sophomores maybe get off twice a month, and maybe a junior.
I forgot the details.
By furlough, does this mean they could go home?
They could go to Brown, maybe to Calvert, maybe to...
get off Saturday afternoon, see.
About that.
They didn't let you off too much.
So they couldn't go to Houston for the weekend or something like that.
Yeah, that's right.
You might get a furlough, go home if you live close.
But you didn't travel around like this now because there wasn't a way to travel.
You either went on the train or walked.
That's right.
There were very few automobiles then.
And the cadets weren't allowed to have one, I understand.
No, no, they didn't have any.
Nobody on the campus had an automobile that had cadets in it.
There was a few cars and bronze, a few on the campus, of course, but that's still in horse and buggy days.
Okay, so you lived first in Austin Hall, then you moved to Milner during your first year there.
Did you live in any other dorms?
Oh, yeah.
I'm not sure whether this boy that I lived in Austin, he may have left on the strike.
Anyhow, he didn't come back for his second year.
I roomed with a young man from Gonzales named Milton Barringer three years.
We roomed in Ross Hall until we graduated.
Was that when you were in A Company?
A Company, that's right.
And he was later president of a British American oil company in Toronto, Canada.
A very fine young man, had a good mind, and made an outstanding record.
And in Ross Hall, you had the stoves, did you, and washstands and so forth like that, being in older Durham?
Or do you remember?
I think they'd put in steam heat at Ross Hall, maybe.
By that time?
Yeah.
And the old bugle deal, the bugle was right down under the window down there.
So we didn't miss any calls.
Couldn't sleep through it.
And this boy in our room with us, I never was very military, but he was.
He was a corporal and a sergeant, 1st Sergeant of the 8th Company.
I believe, and later Captain A Company.
Well, I believe you made it up to 2nd Lieutenant A Company, didn't you?
Oh, yeah, but they did that.
It was forced on them.
I was above privates, and they couldn't make the above privates to go to drills, see.
So they made us all second lieutenants so we'd have to attend.
By they, who do you mean by they?
The bull, the commandant, the military department, see.
There was a bunch of us buck privates, see.
As seniors?
As seniors, yeah.
And they just made us all second lieutenants so we had to attend formation.
That's how simple that was.
I see.
So you had a kind of an over... See, a buck private, he could strangle down to mess all.
He didn't have to attend any.
any formations.
That would be a senior buck probably.
Yeah, he could strike.

I was a sergeant in G Company but roomed in A Company because I worked at this fellow and I'd run the year before in Milner and then we moved over to Ross and I waited till Mitchell, G Company's over in Mitchell.
Well I waited till they filled up then I said, well I can't move over there, there's no place to move, see.
So I went, but I attended formation in G Company during my junior year and was a line sergeant in G Company.
But I was a buck private the next year, but I was rooming in A Company.
You got a demotion the next year.
That's all right.
Yeah, it was good.
As I said, I never was military.
I was.
So when they made a whole bunch of your second lieutenants, you must have had a surplus of second lieutenants.
Oh, we had them.
You bet they had several of them in every company then, you know.
It's all right.
If I do this, I'll inject this thought into it, that it's the finest thing that any young man can have is two years of military.
I think every young man should have two years of military service.
It's...

Some things that you learned that you'll never learn anywhere else, particularly how to take and give orders, because very few people ever live to the point they don't have to take orders somewhere in their long life.
So it's the best training in the world.
I think every young man ought to have two years of military training.
Whether it's in school or otherwise.
It don't make any difference.
I don't care whether he's in school, whether he takes it in college, or whether he takes it in the Army.
Preferably, I'd see them taking the Marine Corps because they've got discipline.
They can all tell you about the freedom of this, that, and the other, but I want to tell you this world today lacks discipline.
We need it.
We need it badly.
We need supervision.
I agree with you.
If ever I want to have a good argument with my wife, I tell her that.
She disagrees with me.
I see by your yearbook that you were also in the Bugle Corps.
I was.
They all got in a big water fight at mail company one night and they caught us all and made us go to the Commodore's office.
write an explanation, and this, that, and the other, and called us all up, and commented on old Levi G. Brown.
He was tough, too.
He was commenting, but he was all right.
And so he says, Mr. Burns says, you're not getting along very good in the Air Company.
But I wasn't because I didn't particularly like the captain, and
They did have a first lieutenant was a nice fellow and a second lieutenant was a nice fellow, but I didn't like the captain at all.
We didn't see eye to eye, but anyhow we all got in a big water fight up on the 34th floor of Milner Hall.
Buckets of water just sluiced and they caught us.
So they sent us all to the Commandant's office for an explanation.
Old Levi Brown told me, he says, Mr. Barnes, you're not getting along very good in the L Company.
He says, we're going to reorganize the bugle corps.
He says, we want to put you in the bugle corps.
I said, why would I have to blow a bugle?
And I never did learn either.
But you stayed in the bugle corps?
I stayed in the bugle corps.
For how long?

short till the balance of that year and that was along in the spring so i wasn't in beautiful johnny garrity and ron hansen and all several of us in there and put a good bunch of boys we had a good time but you never never learned how to blow i never did i could did even noise that's about all uh even though you didn't didn't really learn how did they still have you take a turn at the
Added in the morning or in the afternoon?
I don't think they ever trusted me that far.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Did you have the new mess hall?
No, you didn't have the new one when you started, did you?
No, I reckon we was down to old mess hall when we started there in the fall of 12.
I've eaten down the old one.
Yeah, I believe we had the old mess hall, and later on the next year I believe we had Spiezel Hall.
The old one burned, I guess, while you were fishing.
Yeah, that's right.
The old one burned.
That's right.
The main building burned.
The main building burned while I was tailing the academy.
The old main building.
Yeah, it burned the year before you started, and the mess hall burned in 12.
Yeah, that's right.
And you had a temporary one for a while.
That's right, yeah.
Oh, we got by on it all right.
I think Thursday nights they had T-bone steaks and everybody loved those, of course.
We got by.
We had plenty to eat.
It wasn't too bad.
Pretty monotonous at times?
Oh, yeah.
It gets old.
It's like anything else, you know.
It's been a lot worse.
What did you do for entertainment and recreation if you did anything other than have a water fight done in it?
Oh, we shot dice and played cards.
We had a card game going in L Company for, oh, I don't know.
Poker game?
Oh, pitch principally.
Very little poker.
Had a few dice games.
I learned early in my career that I was not a dice shooter.
I didn't shoot dice much, but we did have a pitch game going most of the time.
I devoted a lot of time to that.
There wasn't much recreation, really.
You kind of had to make your own.
And then you'd get off maybe once a month, maybe you'd go to Braun and see a picture show, and that was about it.
And that old trolley, you know, that was an old gasoline trolley run from Braun to college.
Yeah.
I believe later they made it electric.
Oh yeah, that's right, but that was an old gasoline trolley early.
Yeah.
hadn't been going for more than a year or two when you started there.
And of course there was football in the fall and basketball.
They just started doing basketball to any degree and baseball in the spring.
You could go out there and watch them practice and that stuff.
Of course you drilled it three days a week.
You drilled Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, see.
For how long?
Two hours.
Two hours?
You bet, yeah.
I think two hours.
Spent a good bit of time in class and in lab, too.
That's right.
You had lab classes in the afternoon.
You got up 6 o'clock in the morning in formation.
You had room inspection.
You had things pretty clean, pretty well done up.
Then Sunday morning, every Sunday morning, you had Sunday morning inspection.
Did you have your inspection before or after you went to chapel?
Before you went to chapel, yeah.
You'd go to chapel till 11 o'clock, I believe.
Some old boys went to Sunday school classes.
You had Sunday school before chapel then?
Yeah, we had Sunday morning inspection usually before chapel.
So what, you'd line up on Military Walk and have inspection?
No, room inspection.
Room inspection, so you had to be in the room.
Yeah, you bet.
It had to be clean, too.
Your guns had to be clean, and everything had to be in order.
And that was part of the regular army that came by?
Oh, yeah, absolutely.
But then you also had a daily inspection, didn't you?
Well, of course, that daily inspection.
They'd look in on those rooms every morning to see if your beds were made up.
